{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01B1UcfE9xDDduBWAK8D6jpq","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a full picture:\n- `ray-head`: 1 replica, image `rayproject/ray:2.9.0`, no resources set, exposes GCS (6379) and dashboard (8265) on ClusterIP\n- `ray-worker`: 3 replicas, image `rayproject/ray:2.9.0`, no resources set\n\nThe `ray-head` Deployment has `replicas: 1` (shown in the spec, but this is normal for a head node). The original replica spec is 1, but the `ray-worker` has 3 replicas (scaled up from the default of 1).\nNow I'm putting together a migration plan document that outlines the current state and proposes concrete changes for the next upgrade window, including upgrading the Ray image from 2.9.0 to 2.10.0, adding resource requests and limits for both head and worker nodes, and potentially scaling the workers up to 4 replicas while also reviewing the dashboard service configuration.\n\nFor the resource allocations, I'm thinking through realistic values—the head node needs more capacity for the GCS server, so I'd suggest around 500m CPU and 1Gi memory for requests with 2 CPU and 2Gi limits, while workers could handle 1 CPU and 2Gi for requests with 4 CPU and 4Gi limits. Rather than embedding the plan directly in a kubectl command with special character escaping, I'll write it to a file first and use the `--from-file` approach to create the ConfigMap, which is cleaner and safer.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1340,"cache_read_input_tokens":29580,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1340},"output_tokens":28,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8434144e-e398-4483-8bbb-8fa0262c5972","uuid":"1d7d3493-c328-46bd-9f01-88388883f69a","reques